postcontent: The Mossberg 500 Combo (54264) offers hunters a versatile Pump-Action Shotgun, suited for hunting a wide range of game, including deer, waterfowl, upland birds, and turkey. The Combo pump shotgun comes with 1 vent-ribbed, smoothbore, ported barrel that accepts Accu-Set choke tubes and 1 fully rifled and ported barrel with rifle sights. Twin beads on the ribbed barrel provide quick sight acquisition. The 3" chamber functions with both 3" and 2-3/4" shells to enhance the 500's versatility for shooting a variety of loads. Dual action bars prevent binding and twisting while cycling the action, and a single, large locking lug locks the bolt into the barrel extension, ensuring a solid steel bolt-to-barrel connection. Dual extractors take a solid hold on the shell's rim for reliable extraction. The aluminum alloy receiver keeps weight down and resists corrosion. Hunters can reach the tang quickly with the thumb of either hand, making it naturally ambidextrous. The Mossberg 500 disassembles into sub-components for cleaning and maintenance by unscrewing the magazine cap (which stays on the barrel); the trigger assembly drops out easily with the removal of only 1 pin. For years, military, law enforcement, and hardcore hunters have chosen Mossberg pump shotguns for their simplistic design and reliability. The 500 Pump-Action Shotgun Combo has a hardwood buttstock and forearm and blued barrels.

title: For Sale:  Remington 1882 Antique Double Hammer Gun No FFL
postcontent: Remington Model 1882 manufactured in the 1880’s. There is very little information published on the 1882 or 1883 models but apparently they look the same with the exception of the hammers. Production estimates are about 7500 manufatured, rather rare. It is chambered in 12 gauge & has 30” non-Damascus barrels, choked full & full. It looks to be all original & the serial number 11,798 is found on the receiver, barrels, forearm wood & metal, we have not had it apart further. The only stamping on the exterior is E. REMINGTON & SONS ILLION. N.Y found of the barrel rib. Top lever break action, the receiver, side plates & hammers are case colored, has flash fences, checkered hammer spurs & the barrels are blued. The stocks are straight grained walnut; checkered, round knob pistol grip, widow peaked steel butt plate & the forend has an ebony tip. The shotgun weighs 8 ½ pounds, is 46” long, the LOP is 13 1/8” & 14”, drop @ comb is 2 3/8” & the drop @ heel is 3 1/8”. Mechanically sound, smooth action that opens & closes effortlessly with a tight lock up, hammers cock properly & fall with a nice trigger pull, the extractors work, it is fully functional, I wouldn’t hesitate to fire with the proper ammo. The bore shines brightly with very minor corrosion or imperfections. The end of the left muzzle has a ding which could be easily repaired. There is still a lot of bluing remaining on the barrel turning Patina where the bluing has thinned. No rust issues, just minor handling marks & a few pin-head pits. Some case coloring is visible, more in the protected areas. The stocks are solid with no cracks or repairs, just minor handling marks & a chip of wood missing above the side-plate on the left hand side. It goes unnoticed for the most part, is not a structural concern & no repair is needed. The fluting is still sharp & the checkering is relatively sharp. The condition of this shotgun is quite incredible considering it has been around for over 130 years. Great looking antique production Remington Model 1882 in working order, there can’t be many around any nicer.

title: For Sale:  Used-Hungarian F.E.G AP-7 (ICN4594)
postcontent:
The FEG AP-MBP is a pistol very similar to the PA-63 except in 7.65mm instead of 9x18 Makarov. Being a direct blowback design, these lessor cartridges still have considerable recoil, so in my opinion the smaller chambering of the AP-MBP makes this gun more enjoyable to shoot. This gun was used in Hungary during the communist era as a government issued firearm. My understanding is that they were issued by the Hungarian Police from 1950 to 1957. 7.65mm Browning, also known as .32 ACP and .32 auto, is often considered an anemic chambering by Americans, but in Europe it has commonly been accepted as a military and police cartridge.
The FEG AP is very similar to the German Walther PP but the design has been slightly modified by FEG. It features an aluminum frame. It holds an 8 round magazine of 7.65mm Browning. It has a safety decocker lever and is a traditional double action firearm. The double action pull is very long and heavy. The gun weighs in at approximately 20 ouncesGood clean Bore, Straw finish.

title: For Sale:  Pre-War Kreighoff Drilling Combination Gun 16 Gauge over 8x72 R
postcontent: For Sale I have a Beautiful Krieghoff Waldschutz Drilling in 16 Gauge over 8x72 Rimmed. This Drilling looks to have been carried but not shot that often as the shotgun bores are mirror bright and the rifle bore is bright and shiny with strong rifling. This is the Waldschutz model which was an upgraded version of the Semper drilling with shorter barrels coming in at 22 inches or 55 CM. It also featured dual rifles sights on the rib instead of one single rifle sight one being automatic when the Rifle switch is activated as well as a manual flip up sight. The length of pull is a little over 15" and overall the gun handles very well. The condition remains very good for its age with almost all bluing remaining on the barrels and partial case coloring on the receiver. There is a small dent in the right shotgun barrel but It affects nothing during shooting. I took it to a gunsmith and he said it could be popped out for $50 but he didn't have a 16 gauge plug to run through it to pop it out so if it bothered you that much it could be easily fixed. The wood had several dents and dings but still presents well. The trigger guard is made of horn which was a $100 option on these guns and suprisingly the total for this gun back in 1931 totaled over $1200 US dollars. I found an old price list from Kreighoff and it listed this model at 270 Reisch Marks which with the conversion rate of the time would have cost $1171 plus the extra $50 for the Buffalo Horn trigger guard puts you over $1200. I have this Drilling priced very reasonably for the condition and model which isn't very often seen and its priced resonably close to its original price when purchased new 85 years ago. you wont find another Kreighoff Drilling in this condition for this price anywhere.
